-makers will decide the values of in order to achieve the best outcome in an optimization problem.\"", "\"BOUNDARY CONSTRAINTS\":\"Boundary constraints are the specific limits within which the variables must operate. They form the edges of the feasible region.\"", "\"CORNER POINT METHOD\":\"The corner point method is a technique used in linear programming to find the optimal solution by evaluating the objective function at each vertex of the feasible region.\"", "\"SLACK VARIABLES\":\"Slack variables are added to linear programming constraints to convert inequalities into equalities. They represent unused resources.\"", "\"SURPLUS VARIABLES\":\"Surplus variables are subtracted from linear programming constraints to convert inequalities into equalities. They represent excess resources.\"", "\"SIMPLEX METHOD\":\"The simplex method is an algorithm for solving linear programming problems by moving from one vertex of the feasible region to an adjacent vertex to find the optimal solution.\"", "\"DUAL PROBLEM\":\"The dual problem in linear programming is derived from the primal problem and provides bounds on the optimal value of the primal problem.\"", "\"SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS\":\"Sensitivity analysis in linear programming examines how the optimal solution changes as the parameters of the objective function or constraints are varied.\"", "\"NON-NEGATIVITY CONSTRAINTS\":\"Non-negativity constraints require that the decision variables in a linear programming problem be greater than or equal to zero.\"", "\"BINDING CONSTRAINTS\":\"Binding constraints are constraints that hold as equalities at the optimal solution. They limit the value of the objective function.\"", "\"REDUNDANT CONSTRAINTS\":\"Redundant constraints are constraints that do not affect the feasible region. They do not change the optimal solution.\"", "\"UNBOUNDED SOLUTION\":\"An unbounded solution in linear programming occurs when the objective function can increase indefinitely without violating any constraints.